Photographic plate

Packaging cover of [AGFA](/AGFA) photographic dry glass plates designed for use with metal cassettes, circa 1880
Mimosa Panchroma-Studio-Antihalo Panchromatic glass plates, 9 x 12cm, Mimosa A.-G. Dresden
Negative glass plate

Before the ubiquitous reign of [film](/Photographic_film), the primary medium for capturing images in the nascent and evolving world of photography was the rather formidable [photographic plate](/Photographic_plate). These foundational elements of early image capture were crafted from either robust metal or, more commonly, delicate [glass](/Glass), meticulously coated with a specialized light-sensitive [emulsion](/Photographic_emulsion). They weren't merely components; they were the very canvases upon which the earliest photographic processes—such as the groundbreaking [heliography](/Heliography), the meticulously detailed [daguerreotypes](/Daguerreotype), and the intricate art of [photogravure](/Photogravure)—etched their visual narratives. By the latter half of the 19th century, particularly the late 1800s, glass plates had firmly established their dominance. Their widespread adoption was a testament to their inherent clarity and remarkable reliability, qualities that film, in its infancy, struggled to consistently match. While the 20th century saw their widespread displacement by the advent and popularization of [photographic film](/Photographic_film), photographic plates stubbornly held onto their relevance. They continued to be indispensable for highly specialized scientific and medical applications, a niche where their unique properties remained unchallenged, persisting in these critical roles until the twilight of the 20th century.

History

One might think that progress always means moving to something lighter and more flexible. But for serious imaging, especially in scientific research, glass plates offered a stark, undeniable advantage over their flexible [film](/Photographic_film) counterparts: unwavering stability. They were far less prone to the infuriating bending, curling, or distorting that could plague [film](/Photographic_film), a crucial characteristic, particularly when dealing with the expansive, large-format frames required for wide-field imaging in fields like astronomy. The earliest iterations of these plates relied upon the demanding and time-sensitive [wet collodion process](/Collodion_process). This method required the photographic plate to be coated, exposed, and developed all while the [collodion](/Collodion_process) [emulsion](/Photographic_emulsion) remained wet, a logistical challenge that tethered photographers to their darkrooms, often literally in the field. However, this rather cumbersome wet plate process, with its stringent time constraints and operational complexities, eventually yielded to a more convenient and practical innovation in the late 19th century: the [gelatin](/Gelatin) [dry plates](/Dry_plate). These revolutionary dry plates, pre-coated and ready for use, liberated photographers from the immediate need for a portable darkroom, marking a significant leap forward in photographic convenience and accessibility.

Image resulting from a glass plate negative showing Devil's Cascade in 1900

The ambition of early photography knew few bounds, as evidenced by monumental creations like "The Mammoth." This colossal [view camera](/View_camera), an engineering marvel of its time, weighed a staggering 1,400 pounds (approximately 640&#160;kg). It was meticulously constructed by the ingenious [George R. Lawrence](/George_R._Lawrence) in the year 1899, not for some casual snapshot, but with the singular, audacious purpose of immortalizing "The [Alton Limited](/Alton_Limited)" train, a jewel in the crown of the [Chicago & Alton Railway](/Alton_Railroad). This behemoth of a camera produced images on glass plates of truly epic proportions, each measuring an astonishing 8 feet (2.4&#160;m) by 4.5 feet (1.4&#160;m). Such an undertaking speaks volumes about the dedication and scale of early photographic endeavors, pushing the boundaries of what was technologically possible.

Despite their early dominance and scientific utility, glass plate photographic material began its slow, inevitable retreat from the consumer market during the nascent years of the 20th century. This decline was largely driven by the relentless march of convenience, as increasingly user-friendly and significantly less fragile [photographic films](/Photographic_film) gained traction and widespread adoption among the general public. However, the venerable photographic plate proved remarkably resilient in certain professional niches. Reports indicate that at least one photography business in the bustling city of London continued to rely on these plates for their operations well into the 1970s. Similarly, the Belle Vue Studio in Bradford, another bastion of traditional photography, kept the flame alive until its closure in 1975. Beyond commercial studios, photographic plates remained a critical, widely utilized tool for professional [astrophotography](/Astrophotography) for considerably longer, holding their ground with steadfast resolve as late as the 1990s. Even in the early 21st century, a testament to their enduring appeal and unique aesthetic qualities, workshops are still actively conducted, instructing enthusiasts and artists in the intricate craft of glass plate photography, either as a captivating alternative medium or for specialized artistic expression. It seems some technologies simply refuse to be fully relegated to the annals of history.

Sizes

Photographic plates, much like their later [film](/Photographic_film) counterparts, were produced in a variety of standardized sizes to accommodate different cameras and applications. These dimensions, often bearing quaint, historical names, dictated the scope and detail of the captured image.

| Known as        | Imperial (inches) | Metric (mm) |
| :-------------- | :---------------- | :---------- |
| Quarter-plate   | 3¼ × 4¼           | 83 × 108    |
| Half-plate      | 4¾ × 6½           | 120 × 165   |
| Full-plate      | 6½ × 8½           | 216 × 165   |

These "imperial" and "metric" designations, though seemingly straightforward, reflect a historical period where standardization was a developing concept. The larger the plate, generally, the higher the potential for detail and resolution, making the "Full-plate" a preferred choice for professional work where image quality was paramount. The smaller "Quarter-plate" offered a more portable and economical option, perhaps for less demanding applications or for those with smaller budgets.

Scientific uses

It seems that whenever humanity needed to peer into the unknown, whether it was the vastness of space or the subatomic chaos, these rigid, light-sensitive slabs were deemed indispensable. A testament to their unflinching precision, I suppose.

Astronomy

Indeed, countless pivotal [astronomical surveys](/Astronomical_survey) owe their existence and the invaluable data they provided to the humble photographic plate. Among the most celebrated are the inaugural [Palomar Observatory](/Palomar_Observatory) Sky Survey ([POSS](/National_Geographic_Society_%E2%80%93_Palomar_Observatory_Sky_Survey)) conducted throughout the 1950s, its subsequent, more comprehensive successor, the POSS-II survey, which meticulously charted the heavens through the 1990s, and the comprehensive UK [Schmidt Telescope](/Schmidt_telescope) [survey](/Timeline_of_astronomical_maps,_catalogs,_and_surveys) that focused on the southern [declinations](/Declination) of the celestial sphere. These surveys, etched onto countless glass plates, created an enduring legacy of observational data, a permanent record of the cosmos at specific points in time. Many esteemed [observatories](/Observatory) globally, including the venerable [Harvard College](/Harvard_College_Observatory) and the historic [Sonneberg](/Sonneberg_Observatory), conscientiously maintain vast, priceless archives comprising millions of these photographic plates. These collections are not mere historical curiosities; they serve as a crucial resource, primarily facilitating historical research into the enigmatic behavior of [variable stars](/Variable_star), allowing astronomers to track changes over decades or even centuries.

The discovery of numerous objects within our own solar system transitioned dramatically from painstaking visual observation to the more efficient and accurate method of utilizing photographic plates. This shift marked a new era of astronomical discovery. The pioneering work in discovering [minor planets](/Minor_planet) through photographic plates was spearheaded by the brilliant [Max Wolf](/Max_Wolf), whose efforts began in earnest with his groundbreaking discovery of [323 Brucia](/323_Brucia) in 1891. This marked a significant departure from previous visual search methods. Not long after, in 1898, the first [natural satellite](/Natural_satellite) to be discovered using photographic plates was [Phoebe](/Phoebe_(moon)), one of Saturn's moons, a testament to the medium's newfound capabilities. Perhaps the most celebrated discovery attributed to photographic plates is that of [Pluto](/Pluto), identified in 1930 using a specialized instrument known as a [blink comparator](/Blink_comparator), which allowed astronomers to detect movement by rapidly alternating between two plates taken at different times. Decades later, its enigmatic moon, [Charon](/Charon_(moon)), was also brought to light through this technology. In 1978, a full 48 years after Pluto's own discovery, [U.S. Naval Observatory](/U.S._Naval_Observatory) astronomer [James W. Christy](/James_W._Christy) meticulously examined a subtle, yet distinct, bulge in Pluto's photographic image on a plate, correctly inferring the presence of an orbiting companion.

The rationale behind the persistent use of glass-backed plates, rather than the more flexible [film](/Photographic_film), in the demanding field of astronomy was rooted in their intrinsic physical properties. Glass plates exhibited negligible shrinkage or deformation, both during the chemical development process and under the influence of fluctuating environmental conditions. This dimensional stability was absolutely critical for precise measurements and long-term observations. Several profoundly important applications within [astrophotography](/Astrophotography), notably [astronomical spectroscopy](/Astronomical_spectroscopy) (analyzing the light from celestial bodies) and [astrometry](/Astrometry) (precisely measuring the positions and movements of stars), continued to rely on these plates. They maintained their supremacy until [digital imaging](/Digital_imaging) technologies advanced to a point where their resolution, sensitivity, and processing advantages could finally surpass the established photographic results. This technological transition, however, wasn't immediate. The gradual discontinuation of production of most types of photographic plates by major manufacturers like [Kodak](/Eastman_Kodak) and others, as the market for them inevitably dwindled between 1980 and 2000, effectively signaled the end of most remaining astronomical use, including their crucial role in large-scale sky surveys. It seems that even the most reliable tools eventually yield to the relentless march of technological "progress."

Physics

Photographic plates, with their inherent sensitivity to energy, also served as an indispensable instrument in the early, formative years of [high-energy physics](/High-energy_physics). Their utility stemmed from a fundamental characteristic: they darkened perceptibly when exposed to [ionizing radiation](/Ionizing_radiation). This property made them excellent, albeit passive, detectors. The pioneering physicist [Ernest Rutherford](/Ernest_Rutherford), renowned for his foundational work in nuclear physics, was among the first to systematically harness this characteristic. He utilized photographic plates to meticulously measure the intensity of the various rays—alpha, beta, and gamma—produced during [radioactive decay](/Radioactive_decay), thereby studying their absorption properties in a diverse range of materials. This early application laid crucial groundwork for understanding the nature of radiation. The subsequent development of highly optimized [nuclear emulsions](/Nuclear_emulsion) throughout the 1930s and 1940s, initially within specialized physics laboratories and later refined by commercial manufacturers, marked a significant leap forward in particle detection. These advanced emulsions facilitated the groundbreaking discovery and precise measurement of fundamental particles such as the [pi-meson](/Pi-meson) in 1947 and the [K-meson](/K-meson) in 1949. These pivotal discoveries, directly enabled by the enhanced capabilities of nuclear emulsions, unleashed an unprecedented torrent of new particle discoveries that profoundly reshaped the landscape of physics throughout the latter half of the 20th century.

Electron microscopy

In the realm of microscopic imaging, where stability and flatness are paramount, photographic [emulsions](/Photographic_emulsion) were initially coated onto thin [glass](/Glass) plates for use with [electron microscopes](/Electron_microscope). This choice was not arbitrary; the rigid glass substrate provided a significantly more stable and inherently flatter plane for imaging compared to the early, often less consistent, plastic [films](/Photographic_film). This rigidity ensured minimal distortion and maximum precision in capturing the incredibly fine details revealed by electron beams. However, as materials science advanced, the landscape began to shift. Beginning in the 1970s, a new generation of high-contrast, fine-grain emulsions, now coated on improved, thicker plastic films, emerged from manufacturers like [Kodak](/Eastman_Kodak), Ilford, and DuPont. These advanced films gradually supplanted the traditional glass plates, offering comparable quality with increased flexibility and durability. Yet, even these specialized films have, in turn, largely been superseded by the relentless march of [digital imaging](/Digital_imaging) technologies, which now dominate the field of electron microscopy, offering instant feedback and enhanced processing capabilities.

Medical imaging

The inherent sensitivity of certain specialized photographic plates to [ionizing radiation](/Ionizing_radiation), particularly [X-rays](/X-ray), rendered them exceptionally useful in a variety of [medical imaging](/Medical_imaging) procedures and critical [material science](/Material_science) applications. These plates served as a vital, if somewhat static, means of capturing internal structures and detecting flaws. However, much like their counterparts in other scientific disciplines, these photographic plates have been progressively, and largely, replaced by more advanced, reusable, and digitally readable [image plate](/Image_plate) detectors. These modern detectors, alongside other sophisticated types of [X-ray detectors](/X-ray_detector), offer significant advantages in terms of speed, convenience, and the ability to immediately process and manipulate images digitally, effectively rendering the traditional photographic plate a relic of the past in this field.

Decline

