The earliest forms of flexible [film](/Photographic_film), emerging in the late 1880s, were primarily marketed towards the burgeoning amateur photography market, particularly for use in medium-format cameras. These initial plastic bases, however, suffered from several significant drawbacks. Their optical quality was often subpar when compared to glass, and they possessed an annoying tendency to curl or otherwise fail to provide the perfectly flat, stable support surface that a rigid sheet of [glass](/Glass) inherently offered. Furthermore, at its inception, the production of a transparent plastic base was a considerably more expensive endeavor than manufacturing glass. Despite these early limitations, the relentless drive for convenience eventually prevailed. As manufacturing techniques improved, costs for plastic film bases steadily decreased, and the quality of the film itself saw significant enhancements. Consequently, most amateur photographers, eager for a less cumbersome and fragile alternative, enthusiastically abandoned plates in favor of films. The final nail in the coffin for plates in general photography came with the introduction of large-format, high-quality cut films designed specifically for professional photographers in the late 1910s. Following this innovation, the use of photographic plates for any kind of ordinary photography became an increasingly rare sight, relegated to a niche of highly specialized applications.

The stubborn, yet justified, persistence of photographic plates in critical astronomical and other demanding scientific applications began its inevitable descent in the early 1980s. This decline was catalyzed by the gradual, but ultimately complete, replacement of plates by sophisticated [charge-coupled devices](/Charge-coupled_device) (CCDs). These electronic sensors brought with them a new era of imaging, offering not only outstanding dimensional stability, a characteristic previously exclusive to glass plates, but also a host of other compelling advantages. [CCD](/Charge-coupled_device) cameras boasted significantly higher quantum efficiency, meaning they could capture more light per photon, a linear light response that simplified calibration, and a streamlined process for image acquisition and subsequent [digital image processing](/Digital_image_processing). These capabilities were a game-changer. However, even the largest CCD formats available today (for instance, those boasting 8192 × 8192 pixels) still contend with a fundamental limitation: they do not possess the expansive detecting area and sheer [resolution](/Image_resolution) that many traditional photographic plates could offer. This inherent difference has necessitated that modern astronomical survey cameras employ large arrays of multiple CCDs, meticulously tiled together, in order to achieve the same broad coverage that a single, large photographic plate could once provide.

The manufacture of traditional photographic plates has, perhaps unsurprisingly, been largely discontinued by the once-dominant, widely recognized traditional makers such as [Kodak](/Eastman_Kodak) and [AGFA](/AGFA). The dwindling market demand simply made mass production unsustainable. However, the minimal remaining demand has since been catered to by more specialized Eastern European sources. This niche market is almost exclusively driven by the requirements of [holography](/Holography), a highly specialized imaging technique that continues to demand a recording medium with an exceptionally large surface area and a submicroscopic level of resolution. As of 2014, and largely still true today, currently available electronic image sensors simply cannot match these stringent specifications. In the more romanticized realm of traditional photography, a small, dedicated cadre of historical process enthusiasts actively engage in the painstaking craft of making their own wet or dry plates from raw materials. These artisans then utilize their handmade plates in vintage large-format cameras, preserving and celebrating a photographic tradition that refuses to fade entirely into obsolescence.

Preservation

Given their fragility and the invaluable historical data they encapsulate, the [preservation of photographic plates](/Conservation_and_restoration_of_photographic_plates) has become a critical endeavor for numerous institutions. The delicate [emulsion](/Photographic_emulsion) layer on the plate is susceptible to deterioration over time, and the glass medium itself is inherently fragile, prone to cracking or shattering if not handled and stored with meticulous care and precision. Preventing the irretrievable loss of this rich historical information is paramount.

Historical archives

The esteemed United States [Library of Congress](/Library_of_Congress), a veritable treasure trove of historical documents and artifacts, proudly houses an extensive and significant collection of photographic negatives, encompassing both the earlier wet plate and the later dry plate varieties. These invaluable records span a crucial period from 1855 through to 1900. Among this vast archive, over 7,500 individual negatives from the intensely pivotal period of 1861 to 1865, coinciding with the American Civil War, have been meticulously digitized, ensuring their accessibility and preservation for future generations.

Similarly, the [George Eastman Museum](/George_Eastman_Museum), a world-renowned institution dedicated to the art and history of photography, maintains an impressively extensive collection of photographic plates, a testament to their historical significance. In a remarkable discovery in 1951, wet plate negatives of truly monumental scale—measuring an astounding 4&#160;feet 6&#160;inches (1.37&#160;m) by 3&#160;feet 2&#160;inches (0.97&#160;m)—were reportedly unearthed as part of the famed [Holtermann Collection](/Holtermann_Collection). At the time of their report in March 1955, these were proclaimed to be the largest glass negatives ever discovered. These extraordinary images, which form the breathtaking "Shore Tower" panorama of Sydney Harbour, were meticulously captured in 1875 by the skilled photographer [Charles Bayliss](/Charles_Bayliss). Albumen contact prints, derived directly from these colossal negatives, are among the cherished holdings of the Holtermann Collection, and the original negatives themselves are listed as current holdings within the collection.

Scientific archives

The imperative for the preservation of photographic plates takes on a particularly acute urgency within the field of astronomy. Here, celestial phenomena often unfold at an agonizingly slow pace, spanning decades or even centuries. Consequently, these plates represent an irreplaceable, tangible record of the sky and its myriad astronomical objects, with some observations extending back well over a century. The digitization of astronomical plates has emerged as one of the most effective and popular strategies for their preservation, offering the dual benefit of safeguarding these unique astronomical data while simultaneously providing free and immediate access to a global community of scientists and researchers. This forward-thinking approach has been successfully implemented at the [Baldone Astrophysical Observatory](/Baldone_Astrophysical_Observatory), where approximately 22,000 glass and [film](/Photographic_film) plates from their [Schmidt Telescope](/Schmidt_Telescope) have been meticulously scanned and cataloged, transforming them into a readily accessible digital archive.

Another monumental astronomical plate archive is the Astronomical Photographic Data Archive (APDA), housed at the [Pisgah Astronomical Research Institute](/Pisgah_Astronomical_Research_Institute) (PARI). APDA was established as a direct response to the urgent recommendations put forth by an international consortium of scientists who convened in 2007. Their critical discussions centered on devising the most effective strategies for preserving the world's astronomical plate collections, many of which were facing neglect or the threat of disposal due to storage limitations at various observatories. The discussions revealed that numerous observatories were simply no longer able to adequately maintain their vast plate collections and desperately needed a dedicated, secure repository for them. APDA is singularly dedicated to housing and meticulously cataloging these often-unwanted plates, with the ambitious overarching goal of eventually cataloging every single plate and creating a comprehensive, searchable database of images. This database is envisioned to be accessible via the Internet to the global community of scientists, researchers, and students, democratizing access to this invaluable historical data. APDA currently boasts an impressive collection of over 404,000 photographic images, meticulously gathered from more than 40 observatories worldwide. These irreplaceable artifacts are safely housed in a purpose-built, secure facility equipped with advanced environmental controls to ensure their long-term stability. The facility is also home to several high-precision plate scanners, including two particularly advanced units, GAMMA I and GAMMA II. These were originally constructed for [NASA](/NASA) and the [Space Telescope Science Institute](/Space_Telescope_Science_Institute) (STScI) and were instrumental in the work of a team, led by the late Barry Lasker, to develop the foundational [Guide Star Catalog](/Guide_Star_Catalog) and the Digitized Sky Survey—both critical resources used to precisely guide and direct the iconic [Hubble Space Telescope](/Hubble_Space_Telescope). APDA's robust networked storage system is capable of storing and analyzing an immense volume of data, exceeding 100 terabytes, further solidifying its role as a vital hub for astronomical heritage.

A significant historical collection of photographic plates originating from the renowned [Mt. Wilson Observatory](/Mount_Wilson_Observatory) is meticulously preserved and made available at the [Carnegie Observatories](/Carnegie_Observatories). This archive represents a crucial window into the early 20th-century astronomical observations. The associated metadata for these plates is readily accessible via a comprehensive, searchable database, allowing researchers to efficiently locate specific observations. Furthermore, a substantial portion of these invaluable plates has already undergone the critical process of digitization, ensuring their long-term preservation and broader accessibility for scientific inquiry and historical research.

